ounters with Islam during a period which it argues marked a new departure in Anglo-Muslim relations. This approach illuminates the role of Islam in the creation of English national identities within the global cultural system of the British Empire. This book would appeal to those with an interest in British imperial history; Islam; gender, feminism, and women’s studies; slavery and race; the formation of national identities; global processes; Orientalism; and Middle Eastern studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAntislavery movementszEgypt. 0aChristianity and other religionsxIslam. 0aIslamxRelationsxChristianity. 0aProstitutionzEgyptxHistoryy19th century. 0aProstitutionzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Muslim relations.  aBritish Empire.  aBritish Turk.  aBritish and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society.  aBritish identity politics.  aBritish imperial culture.  aEnglish activism.  aEnglish national identities.  aIslam.  aMuslim woman.  aanti-slavery campaign.  afemale slavery.  agender conflicts.  aharem.  alate nineteenth century.1 aRobinson-Dunn, Diane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611863940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526118639423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526118639/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles